<DOCNO> AP880621-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a white housesponsored conference on drugs 
said tuesday that legalization of drugs would be a profound 
mistake and society should instead expand and stiffen measures 
already in use including screening in the workplace and imposing 
the death penalty for trafficking 
such measures would include making the department of defense the 
primary agency for air and sea surveillance of drug trafficking 
extending antidrug policies to every employee in every private 
and public workplace and stiffening mandatory penalties for 
traffickers including addition of the death penalty for drug 
dealers who commit murder 
the us national policy must be zero tolerance for illegal 
drugs said the final report of the white house conference for a 
drug free america established by president reagan last year 
the legalization of illicit drugs is not a solution but 
rather a profound mistake the report said to legalize drugs 
is to make them more readily available and as an inevitable 
consequence more widely used and this is simply unacceptable 
illicit drugs are far too destructive to the health of our citizens 
and the strength of our national character 
included in the more than 100 recommendations are creation of a 
drug czar with cabinet rank increased taxes on beer wine liquor 
and tobacco to finance the antidrug fight and setting up a 
national drug prevention agency 
whether we are family members or coworkers of addicts 
passengers on airplanes or trains piloted by users victims of 
brutal and wanton violence induced by mind altering drugs 
travelers facing the menace of drugged drivers on our highways or 
simply taxpayers we are all victims of illicit drug use said 
lois haight herrington chairman of the conference 
meanwhile the house merchant marine and fisheries committee 
unanimously approved legislation to curb government seizures of 
boats cars and other vehicles under the zero tolerance 
antidrug policy the panel barred the seizures whih have prompted 
many complaints unless theres evidence that the owners or 
operators knew illegal drugs were present 
transportation secretary james burnley called the legislation 
an outrageous action that would gut the policy and 
undermine efforts of his department to keep drugs off boats and 
improve marine safety 
the drug report which herrington will present to reagan next 
week stressed prevention and education and it earned this accolade 
from education secretary william j bennett 
weve heard a million proposals from a thousand people but 
here is a comprehensive tough and practical set of 
recommendations i applaud this report 
more than 5000 people including former addicts entertainment 
and sports figures teachers doctors parents students judges 
and prevention specialists took part in six regional and one 
national conference 
the report said the president should promote a strong 
straightforward easytounderstand policy that prevention is 
essential to rid this country of its drug problem 
this policy must be backed by adequate funds the report 
said 
it called for more spending in the criminal justice system and 
the building of more prisons and said all people in custody should 
be tested for illicit drug use 
penalties should be stiffened to include mandatory minimum 
sentences for drug traffickers those using youths to distribute 
drugs and those selling to youth both adult and juvenile drug 
traffickers should be treated as serious offenders and sentenced 
accordingly 
the drug lords of this world deserve our greatest 
condemnation the conference said but while participants were 
not unanimous on use of the death penalty a clear consensus 
emerged that no other sentence seems to be appropriate 
in the workplace both public and private the report said 
there should be a strong antidrug policy that begins before a new 
employee is on the payroll 
prehire mechanisms should include a clear written statement to 
applicants that they will be subject to a drug test or a physical 
examination that includes drug testing the report said 
the report cautioned that care should be taken so the screening 
will be used only as a mechanism to prevent hiring of drug users 
it also recommended testing for cause when accidents 
absenteeism or abnormal behavior indicate a potential drug problem 
and it advocated random testing whenever there is a need to 
ensure that workers are beyond question fit for safe healthy and 
secure work assignments 
there are specific recommendations for a drugfree 
transportation system and for preventing drugs in sports a 
section on media and entertainment calls for avoiding the 
glamorizing of drug use and for a movie rating system that would 
take drug content into account 
the conference was especially critical of the state department 
for giving the international war on drugs a low priority and for 
assigning law enforcement activities overseas to diplomats 
</TEXT>
