<TEXT>
canadian prime minister brian mulroney disclosed 
tuesday that canada expelled a group of soviet diplomats last week 
for improper and unacceptable behavior 
canadian officials said 17 soviet diplomats and trade 
representatives in ottawa and montreal were either expelled or told 
not to return in cases where they had already left the country 
mulroney made the disclosure at a final summit news conference 
when asked about the expulsion by a canadian broadcasting corp 
reporter who sought confirmation that there had been expulsions 
for industrial espionage 
i will confirm the government of canada took some action last 
week in regard to the improper and unacceptable behavior by 
representatives of the soviet government in canada mulroney said 
he said canadian security officers presented the government with 
rather delicate information and certain people were 
expelled 
foreign minister joe clark will make a statement on the action 
in parliament on wednesday mulroney said 
the canadian press news agency quoting unidentified sources in 
ottawa said scientific and technological information was believed 
to be the soviets main target 
the agency said eight of the soviets have left canada since the 
expulsion two of them worked at the soviet embassy in ottawa and 
the others were based in montreal with diplomatic status the other 
nine soviets had left canada in recent months all were declared 
persona non grata and told they could not return 
canadian press said the expulsions appeared to have no 
connection with the arrest last week on spying charges of stephen 
joseph ratkai a nova scotian of hungarian descent ratkai was 
accused under canadas official secrets act with gathering 
classified us military documents from a submarinetracking 
station at argentia newfoundland 
mulroney said that despite the summits endorsement of soviet 
leader mikhail s gorbachevs reforms western leaders were under 
no illusions about the soviet union 
</TEXT>
