a federal judge on monday agreed to dismiss 
the countrys largest desegregation suit paving the way for an end 
to the 25year battle between the naacp and the nations 
secondlargest school district 
the parties were given 60 days to work out a settlement before 
the decision becomes final 
the action arises out of the recognition that precious 
little can be accomplished to desegregate a school system that 
presently is just barely 17 percent white said district counsel 
peter james 
grover g hankins general counsel for the national association 
for advancement of colored people said he was hopeful negotiations 
would offer some substantial relief to minority students 
the suit was first filed by the naacp in state court in 1963 
and moved to federal court in 1981 
in the mid1960s district enrollment was more than 55 percent 
white today however 83 percent of the districts nearly 590000 
students are from minority groups hispanics at 568 percent form 
the largest ethnic minority group followed by blacks at 177 
percent asians and pacific islanders at 82 percent and american 
indians at 03 percent whites make up 169 percent of the total 
enrollment 
among proposals being considered to enhance opportunities of 
minority students is the expansion of a oneyear pilot program that 
involved overhauling the administration and teaching staffs at 
lowachieving innercity schools that was accompanied by new 
curricula with an emphasis on reading and writing 
some evidence has showed that the changes have brought higher 
test scores james said 
us district judge a wallace tashimas action would end the 
largest desegregation lawsuit in the country after more than 20 
years of costly legal battles 
the naacp alleged that the district illegally discriminated 
against black students through its policies and actions a state 
court ordered the district to reassign and bus students to achieve 
integration from 1978 to 1981 
mandatory busing ceased when voters approved proposition 1 in 
1979 which barred state courts from ordering busing as a remedy 
for segregation 
the antibusing initiative would not prevent a federal court 
from ordering busing however if it found the district in 
violation of federal law 
since mandatory busing ended the district provided a voluntary 
integration approach relying partly on magnet schools which 
offer specialized instruction and which must conform to ratios that 
permit up to 60 percent to 70 percent minority enrollment 
