<TEXT>
wilford leach 59 the tony awardwinning 
director of the mystery of edwin drood and the pirates of 
penzance as well as principal director for the new york 
shakespeare festival died saturday of cancer 
from 1958 until 1981 he was a professor of theater and film at 
sarah lawrence college in bronxville 
leach also worked as a playwright and director at la mama the 
experimental offoffbroadway theater and eventually became its 
artistic director among his shows produced there were carmilla 
and corfax 
leach first worked for the festival in 1977 as an associate 
director for its central park production of henry v among the 
other outdoor productions directed by leach for the festival were 
alls well that ends well othello the taming of the 
shrew and twelfth night 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sallie martin who was known as the mother of 
gospel music died saturday at age 92 
mrs martin started singing in a baptist church her search for 
work brought her to cleveland and then chicago where in 1932 she 
teamed up with the rev thomas m dorsey 
together they crisscrossed the south mrs martin sang dorseys 
syncopated hymns at churches and meeting halls along the way after 
performances she sold sheet music for 10 cents a copy 
mrs martin was featured in the documentary film say amen 
somebody 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
william h hutt an economist who 
championed free enterprise and attacked south africas apartheid 
system of racial separation died sunday he was 89 
hutt wrote 12 books and numerous scholarly articles many of 
which criticized the theories of john maynard keynes that encourage 
government deficits and more government control over the economy 
he taught at the university of cape town in south africa from 
1926 until 1965 and was a leading critic of apartheid in the 
1940s hutt helped found the mont pelerin society an international 
organization of scholars supporting free enterprise 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jay c holbrook the youngest general manager 
of a major professional opera company when he assumed the post with 
the baltimore opera co at the age of 27 in 1980 died sunday of 
cancer at the age of 35 
holbrook who began as a volunteer in the operas wardrobe and 
props department worked his way up as public relations director 
and assistant general manager and earned two twoyear 
apprenticeinternship grants from the national opera institute at 
the kennedy center for the performing arts 
he was named to the general managers post in 1980 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jack leonard a big band singer who recorded 
hundreds of songs with the tommy dorsey orchestra died friday he 
was 73 
leonard joined dorseys group in 1937 and recorded more than 200 
songs with the orchestra before leaving the band for military 
service at the beginning of world war ii 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
james thornton chandler a longtime 
television and movie character actor died june 14 of lung cancer 
at age 66 
chandlers most famous role was as inspector regan in the 
television series tracer in the 1950s he also appeared in 
western and police shows as well as commercials 
