crop losses because of weather if recent hot dry weather 
continues it could stress the crop but nothing like the midwest 
drought 
weve been lucky for the last three harvests said mick 
we barely made a crop then received extremely timely rains 
going into april we were in a drought situation ourselves the 
rains in april may and june saved the crops 
because of various government land setaside programs the total 
washington state wheat acreage is at its lowest in two decades but 
the total yield for the state is expected to be average or just 
below average mick said 
barley and corn growers also should benefit mick said because 
barley prices are closely related to corn prices and the midwest 
corn crop has been severely hurt by the drought 
although the prices paid for wheat are expected to rise 
consumers should barely feel the increase mick said 
