litigation 
in 1983 the reagan administration sued the states higher 
education system alleging racial discrimination the lawsuit was 
filed after two years of efforts to settle the case among the 
college presidents and state school officials failed 
us district judge uw clemon the first black federal trial 
judge in alabama ruled after a 22day trial in 1985 that 
authorities would have to take steps to racially integrate such 
staterun schools as auburn the university of alabama and troy 
state clemon described auburn as the states most segregated 
university an opinion now void 
but the 11th us circuit court of appeals ruled last oct 6 
that clemon should have disqualified himself because as a former 
state legislator he actively participated in the very events and 
shaped the very facts that are at issue in this suit 
clemon once served as chairman of the state senate rules 
committee in that role the appeals court said he played a 
critical role in the confirmation of those individuals nominated 
for positions on the board of trustees of the defendant 
institutions 
the appeals court however rejected arguments that clemon 
should have disqualified himself because of his past civil rights 
activity and because his children may some day attend some of the 
schools involved 
to disqualify minority judges from major civil rights 
litigation solely because of their minority status is 
intolerable the appellate court said 
the appellate ruling sent the case back for a new trial before 
us district judge sam pointer jr of birmingham 
the appeal acted on monday was filed by alabama state university 
and alabama aampm university two predominantly black schools 
officials at both schools say their integration attempts have been 
thwarted by official state policies and individuals 
