crops and livestock continue to suffer from 
drought in much of the nation but the effects vary widely the 
governments joint agricultural weather facility reported tuesday 
precipitation across the northern great plains did very little 
to ease the drought and improve crop condition during the week of 
june 1319 the facility said the lack of moisture combined 
with high temperatures stressed crops and slowed growth throughout 
most of the eastern half of the nation 
about 23 percent of the winter wheat acreage had been harvested 
by june 19 6 percentage points ahead of a year ago as near ideal 
weather pushed the harvest as far north as illinois the report 
said 
corn was good to fair in the central great plains and fair in 
most other major producing areas the report said corn silking 
was limited mostly to the southeast and delta georgias corn was 
more advanced with some acreage finishing the kernel dough stage 
and entering dent 
the report on the corn crop added the average stalk height 
exceeded the average in illinois extreme dry conditions stressed 
corn in ohio but earlier plantings fare better than late 
plantings the extreme heat rolled corn leaves in nebraska 
soybean plantings were 93 percent completed in the major 
production states by june 19 most planting during the week was in 
the corn belt and central great plains 
the lack of moisture hampered and in some cases halted 
planting in the delta and southeast the report said soybeans 
were mostly fair condition but available moisture kept condition 
good to fair in the central great plains soybeans suffered the 
most in the delta and appalachian states where condition was fair 
to poor 
