<TEXT>
an international agency has set up a task force to 
examine ways to relieve airport congestion and flight delays that 
have reached a crisis situation in europe a spokesman for the 
group said tuesday 
the task force held its first meeting may 25 in montreal where 
it mapped out a working plan to tackle problems created by an 
increase in aircraft takeoffs and landings especially in europe 
said international air transport association spokesman david kyd 
kyd said in an interview with the associated press that aircraft 
movements in europe had increased by 7 percent this year compared 
with 1987 and that last years level may double by the year 2002 
it is now a crisis situation everybodys waking up to it 
he said 
the sixmember committee will examine the traffic problem 
worldwide but is starting with europe where the problem is most 
acute kyd said 
one idea the task force was studying was the possibility of 
ending night curfews at airports in order to increase their 
capacity because new quiet jets can land almost with their 
engines shut down and therefore create less noise he said 
the task force also was looking at the entire air traffic 
control system and is likely to encourage governments to hire more 
air traffic controllers and raise their salaries kyd said 
the task force will meet again in september in london he said 
