<DOCNO> AP880621-0197 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency said 
tuesday it plans to designate 215 more toxic wastes sites as 
eligible for money from the superfund toxic waste dump cleanup 
program 
in addition 14 more sites owned by federal agencies were 
proposed for the national priority list for cleanups though they 
are not eligible for superfund money 
the planned update of the list the seventh since the program 
began in 1982 would be the largest since june 1984 when 244 sites 
were announced 
tuesdays proposals would bring the priority list to 1177 sites 
799 formally designated and 378 awaiting designation 
in addition three sites have been deleted from the list because 
cleanup work is complete and proposals to list 30 more are being 
dropped because the agency now believes cleanups are better 
performed under other laws 
elaine stanley deputy head of superfund enforcement said 
actions are under way at most of the 30 sites all of which are 
owned by permit holders under the federal hazardous waste disposal 
laws 
jack mcgraw deputy assistant epa administrator in charge of 
superfund told reporters the change might even speed cleanups 
because many of the 30 are controlled by large companies who are 
eager to go ahead and try to reduce what they call their 
liability inventory 
thirteen of the 215 proposed sites involve hazardous waste 
facilities where epa does not believe the waste law can be used 
because the owner refuses to negotiate or for some other reason 
generally it takes a year to 18 months after proposal for 
public comment and agency response before a site is formally added 
to the priority list although epa sometimes begins studies of 
possible remedies before the final designation the agency says 97 
percent of proposed sites wind up on the list proposals generally 
are made once a year 
epa has 29463 places in its computers as potential hazardous 
waste sites and has completed investigations at 8875 only the 
worst threats to health and the environment according to a 
complicated numerical scoring system are proposed for the priority 
list 
the agency has said it expects about 2500 sites on the list 
eventually 
once on the list the site becomes eligible for 90 percent 
federal financing of the cleanup with the balance coming from the 
state unless it is owned by a state or local agency the federal 
government will pay only half the cleanup cost of those 
but before federal and state money is used epa tries to get the 
polluters responsible to clean up the site sometimes those people 
are bankrupt cannot be found or dispute their responsiblity epa 
can go ahead and do the work and seek reimbursement later 
the agency says it and the states have secured 600 million to 
700 million in cleanups from responsible parties 191 court cases 
are under way seeking 258 million and epa has been reimbursed for 
78 million in cleanup work it performed 
spending about 15 billion a year superfund is simultaneously 
one of the nations largest environmental programs and one of the 
largest public works programs 
mcgraw said epa tried to propose as many sites as possible to 
clear the pipeline before it begins changing the scoring system 
this summer to meet congressional directives 
those changes will among other things take into account 
threats to health through the food chain give greater weight to 
abandoned wells and try to account for potential later emissions of 
contaminants into the air 
the superfund program came in for renewed criticism in recent 
days 
last friday the congressional office of technology assessment 
said epa was largely ignoring congressional orders to prefer 
permanent cleanups such as incineration or waste treatment methods 
over leaving the waste in the ground and was overestimating costs 
of treatment 
on monday a waste treatment trade group and six environmental 
organizations echoed otas findings in testimony before a house 
subcommittee they also contended that epa was planning to leave 
widely varying waste concentrations behind when cleanups are 
complete 
we have a technical response to each criticism of specific 
cleanup decisions epa assistant administrator winston porter told 
the subcommittee he argued there was simply not enough money for 
incineration at every site 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

