<TEXT>
new hampshire on tuesday marked the 200th 
anniversary of its decisive role in uniting the nation under the 
constitution with a plea to remember all those wonderful purposes 
for which our government was formed 
the list of festivities commemorating new hampshires ninth and 
deciding vote to ratify the constitution included a speech by 
former us chief justice warren burger a lobster dinner for 1200 
on the statehouse lawn and bellringing by hundreds of children 
using a replica of the liberty bell 
new hampshires ratification created the united states in the 
true sense of a nation said burger chairman of the commission 
of the bicentennial of the us constitution 
when new hampshire took this action we really had a united 
states of america for the first time burger said during a 
statehouse ceremony 
supporters of the constitution knew the value of a power 
of any kind depends on having it in some kind of harness and that 
is the genius of our system 
burger also helped unveil a commemorative stamp portraying the 
old man of the mountain a granite formation in the white 
mountains that is the state symbol 
during a morning service at st pauls episcopal church the 
rev david glendinning urged americans to never lose touch with 
all those wonderful purposes for which our government was formed 
we are still and need to be one people he said adding 
that it is critical that americans not be overwhelmed by the 
institution of government 
state rep russell chase of the committee that planned the 
observance said its goal was to to learn more to know more to 
appreciate more the institution that has carried us these 200 
years 
new hampshire became the ninth state to ratify the constitution 
on june 21 1788 the vote by the states ratifying convention was 
5747 
the 13 original colonies already united by the articles of 
confederation had agreed the previous year in philadelphia that 
nine votes would be needed to ratify the new constitution which 
created a strong central government 
the ratification vote ended a long bitter debate federalists 
argued a strong government was needed to provide stability and pull 
the country out of a postwar recession antifederalists said the 
constitution laid the groundwork for the kind of tyrannical central 
government they fought in the revolutionary war 
religion also was an issue as many new hampshire residents 
opposed a passage eliminating any test of religion as a 
qualification for public office 
federalist politicking gained force because eight states 
delaware pennsylvania new jersey georgia connecticut 
massachusetts maryland and south carolina already stood behind 
the document 
five days after new hampshire voted virginia became the 10th 
state to ratify the constitution 
</TEXT>
