<TEXT>
the percentage of jobless workers drawing 
unemployment benefits declined for the fourth year in 1987 as more 
states tightened their eligibility requirements according to a 
study released tuesday 
in a 14page analysis of labor department records the center on 
budget and priorities a liberal foundationfinanced research 
group said the unemployment insurance system protected only about 
315 percent of the jobless last year 
an average of 51 million of the 74 million unemployed 
workers each month in 1987 did not receive unemployement insurance 
benefits the center said 
the 315 percent of jobless workers drawing benefits which 
across the country average 139 a week is the lowest on record 
dating back to 1955 according to the report the respective rates 
of coverage in 1986 and 1985 were 327 percent and 329 percent 
coverage varied sharply among the states ranging from a low of 
166 percent of the unemployed workers receiving benefits in 
virginia to a high of 585 percent in rhode island 
the maximum benefits also differ widely from state to state 
according to 1988 labor department data alabama is the lowest 
providing covered unemployed workers with a maximum of 120 a week 
massachusetts is the highest at 354 per week 
the center said seven straight years of national unemployment 
rates of 7 percent or greater 1980 to 1986 forced many states 
to raise their eligibility requirements and cut benefits to keep 
their unemployment insurance funds solvent and replace borrowings 
from the federal trust fund 
it quoted a house ways and means committee report that 37 states 
in 1987 increased their earnings requirements for drawing maximum 
benefits while only three states relaxed them 
</TEXT>
