<TEXT>
a federal safety board urged broader testing 
for drugs among railroad workers tuesday when drug use is 
suspected but the panel did not endorse a farranging random 
testing program for the industry as urged by the transportation 
department 
the national transportation safety board called on the federal 
government and industry to step up its programs aimed at finding 
drug users among railroad workers it said last year 29 railroad 
accidents involved some drug or alcohol use and in 10 cases the use 
was linked directly to the cause of the accident 
a federal railroad administration rule which went into effect in 
early 1987 requires drug tests to be performed after an accident 
but the rule applies only to accidents involving a fatality or more 
than 500000 damage 
the ntsb said the requirement for such tests should be broadened 
to any accident involving an injury or damage of 150000 and also 
be required whenever a personss work habits or actions such as 
chronic absenteeism indicates an alcohol or drug problem 
the safety board also said the federal railroad administration 
should require railroad employees involved in safetyrelated jobs 
to obtain medical certificates and undergo periodic medical tests 
that include drug screening 
the safety board has no authority to impose such requirements 
and may only make recommendations to the fra and the railroad 
industry 
the board praised the fras postaccident drug and alcohol 
testing requirements but urged that they be broadened to include 
more workers including supervisors whose actions might be 
connected with an accident 
it also called for tests to be conducted more quickly after an 
accident saying in some cases last year workers were not tested 
for 13 hours to 26 hours after an accident 
the transportation department has proposed a wideranging drug 
testing requirement for the railroad industry it currently is 
going through the public hearing stages before being developed into 
a final regulation 
the departments proposal includes random testing for drugs 
among railroad employees the safety board however has not 
endorsed the random testing approach 
ntsb chairman jim burnett said tuesday that for random tests to 
be effective far more tests would have to be required than 
currently is being planned 
he said the government and industry would be more successful in 
ridding railroads of drug problems by targeting tests toward 
those workers who are suspected of drug use through their actions 
or involvement in work rule violations or accidents 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

