<TEXT>
the united nations which is on the edge 
of financial ruin is spending 74 million on the special session 
on disarmament that ends this week 
a budget document obtained tuesday by the associated press 
estimates the costs of the fourweek general assembly session at 
417 million a series of preparatory sessions at 267 million 
and un payments for travel by delegates from the poorest nations 
at 556500 
the document dating from november 1986 took estimates of 
inflation into account and provided figures in anticipated 1988 
dollar values 
un spokeswoman nadia younes said specialsession costs are 
paid out of the regular un budget which is about 800 million 
this year she also noted the united nations may not spend all the 
funds allocated for the session 
last friday secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar said the 
united nations could close down by late october if member nations 
do not pay the 691 million in overdue membership fees 
the united states has withheld 467 million over several years 
insisting the organization cut its staff and adopt budget reforms 
the ap had requested information on the cost of the session that 
has been attended by delegates from more than 86 of the 159 un 
member nations 
many delegation leaders addressed the assembly and all of the 
groups are presenting position papers and news releases in a 
blizzard of documents 
the largest single budget item for the session is for 
documentation 118 million verbatim records of the sessions 
were estimated to cost 109 million and translations 920000 
preparatory meetings included a twoweek committee session in 
1987 budgeted at 633800 and two committee meetings in 1988 
costing 1074 million and 966000 
the session is scheduled to end saturday with the adoption of 
resolutions on nuclear chemical conventional and spacedbased 
weapons no breakthroughs are expected with the final document to 
be adopted by consensus 
america and most of its western allies are seeking a modest 
resolution dealing with progress in disarmament talks and avoiding 
emphasis on nuclear disarmament 
the soviet union made a sweeping proposal to eliminate all 
nuclear arms by the year 2000 an immediate ban on nuclear weapons 
tests and a multinational naval force under un control 
this is the third special session on disarmament in 10 years 
the previous meetings were in 1978 and 1982 
