catholicism was an issue in the 1960 campaign whereas religion is 
not generally seen as a barrier to political office today 
that suggests how far we have come in the past 28 years 
estrich said 
syndicated columnist mary mcgrory recalled how television played 
a much smaller role in the 1960 campaign which she covered than 
it does today although the televised debates in 1960 were hailed 
as a sign of televisions first significant impact on presidential 
politics 
the panelists also discussed changes in rhetoric and 
speechmaking during campaigns changes they said were largely 
dictated by the demands of television and the evolution of the 
image of the presidency since 1960 
