preservation of matagorda island habitat for 
wintering whooping cranes and other endangered species of birds 
entered the home stretch when a senate committee approved 
legislation to buy the last bit of privately held land on the 
barrier island officials said tuesday 
this is important not only for whooping cranes but for water 
fowl shore birds and herons egrets and song birds said brent 
giezentanner manager of the nearby aransas pass national wildlife 
refuge 
a senate appropriations subcommittee late monday approved 
spending 55 million to purchase 5017 acres at the southern tip 
of the texas gulf coast island 
the us fish and wildlife service will buy the land at cost 
from the texas nature conservancy and when the deal goes through 
all the land on the island will be in either federal or state 
ownership according to the office of sen phil gramm rtexas 
but a gramm staffer said it still is unclear how the land will 
be managed with debate centering on whether it should be the state 
or federal government or both the state controls 24893 acres and 
when the final purchase goes through the federal government will 
control 30502 acres 
as the whooping crane flock grows some of the endangered birds 
have wintered on matagorda island rather than at the aransas refuge 
this is going to preserve and protect their habitat from 
development said giezentanner there are only two barrier 
islands in texas that are not developed to some degree matagorda 
and adjacent san jose 
