<TEXT>
when your companys sales and earnings are 
soaring whats the problem how to make the good times last 
that is the textbook situation right now confronting micron 
technology of boise idaho a manufacturer of computer memory chips 
in the past few years most american producers of socalled 
dynamic random access memory chips or drams were driven out of 
the business by intense competition from large japanese 
manufacturers 
joseph parkinson microns chairman has described what happened 
then as a hailstorm of illegal selling of products here in the 
us at below their foreignmade cost to produce 
when the united states and japan reached an agreement covering 
international trade in the chips however micron as one of the 
few independent survivors was suddenly in the right place at the 
right time 
with supplies of chips reduced and demand getting stronger all 
the time prices spiraled upward 
after posting large losses in its 1986 and 1987 fiscal years 
micron recently reported a 5465 million profit for the first nine 
months of its fiscal 1988 through june 2 on revenues of 18709 
million 
in the last five fiscal quarters microns revenues have climbed 
from 228 million to 295 million to 432 million to 533 
million to 856 million 
you cant turn things around so drastically without attracting 
the attention of wall street analysts and investors 
microns stock with its ticker symbol dram has made regular 
appearances lately among the most active issues in the 
overthecounter markets national market system from a low of 4 
last year the stock has jumped to as high as 26 this month 
the question facing microns management customers and its 
followers on wall street is what happens to chip prices from here 
on will the shortage persist even as micron adds a new plant next 
year and other bigger companies size up the profits to be made 
expert opinion runs the full range from yes to no one analyst 
queried by the new york times maintained that the shortage will 
last well into 1989 and i think its going to get worse 
said an industry official it will ease toward the end of the 
third quarter and will end in the fourth quarter of this year 
in this kind of volatile uncertain environment micron has just 
disclosed a strategy aimed at increasing the stability of its 
business and enhancing its onceshaky standing 
parkinson the chief executive announced that the company would 
offer to sell chips to customers under longterm contracts that 
couldnt be canceled rather than the shortterm contracts that 
cover most of its sales now 
the move isnt he asserted an attempt to grab the brass ring 
of higher prices while they last but rather an effort to assure 
reasonable prices on the assumption its a longterm 
relationship 
actually wall street analysts who follow the company say 
micron has more on its mind than prices 
in offering contracts to the big names of the hightechnology 
