government leaders tuesday moved to shore up 
japanese farming after acceding to american demands to lower 
barriers on imported beef and oranges 
key cabinet ministers and officials in the governing liberal 
democratic party emerged from a hastily called meeting tuesday 
morning with a broad outline of steps to ease the transition for 
the nations farmers 
they included trimming production costs subsidizing farmers 
buying up farmland and encouraging tangerine growers to convert 
their plots to other uses according to a statement released by the 
government 
the measures were announced one day after agriculture minister 
takashi sato and us trade representative clayton yeutter signed 
an agreement that could double the imports of american beef and 
oranges by 1991 to 1 billion a year 
the agreement came after months of negotiations and complaints 
by the united states against japans restrictive import quotas 
also tuesday the ministry of agriculture forestry and 
fisheries announced sato would head for australia on wednesday to 
work out a new beef import pact with officials in canberra 
australia provides about 60 percent of japans beef imports while 
american beef accounts for about a third 
the government statement called for drastic measures to 
stabilize the price of japanese beef calves said to cost about 10 
times as much as their american equivalents many japanese beef 
producers rely on calves sold by breeders 
