<TEXT>
the federal judge who ruled in polaroid corps 
landmark 57 billion patent infringement suit against eastman 
kodak co withdrew from the case tuesday because her late 
motherinlaw owned 100000 in kodak stock 
it was the second time in as many weeks that us district court 
judge rya zobel pulled out of a case because of an alleged conflict 
of interest 
in a statement tracing her involvement in the polaroidkodak 
case zobel said neither side objected to her motherinlaws 
holdings at the outset of proceedings in 1981 
the court informed all parties of the holdings before 
opening statements and the taking of any evidence zobel wrote 
throughout the 75 days of trial kodaks silence continued 
zobel stated kodak remained silent even after she ruled in 1985 
that the rochester nybased camera company had violated nine 
polaroid patents when it entered the instant camera market she 
said kodak also did not raise the issue during a lengthy appeal 
process 
shortly after her motherinlaw died zobel on may 9 told 
attorneys from both sides she intended to recuse herself from the 
case because she and her husband had become the beneficiaries of 
her motherinlaws estate 
the judge acquiesced after both sides encouraged her to continue 
in the case and asked her for time to research the situation 
but in a motion filed june 15 in us district court kodak 
called for zobels immediate disqualification and dismissal of all 
of her rulings in the case since october 1981 including the 1985 
patent ruling 
kodak also recommended an award of less than 200 million to 
polaroid for any profits lost to kodaks line of instant cameras 
and film which ceased production under a court order on jan 9 
1986 
noting the delay in kodaks action zobel wrote 
to date neither party has submitted any authority even 
suggesting the incorrectness of the courts stated postion indeed 
for the first time since october 5 1981 kodak asks for recusal 
kodak spokesman henry kaska refused to comment on why the firm 
waited seven years before objecting to zobels holdings but said 
there may have been some misunderstanding at the may 9 meeting 
our counsel had not understood the judge to have made final 
determination to withdraw he said our counsel understood the 
judge asked the parties for their views on the subject and our 
motion was in response to that request 
harry johnson a spokesman for cambridgebased polaroid said 
the case was reassigned to judge a david mazzone he said polaroid 
believed zobels rulings would stand 
the damages portion of the case is to begin in january 1989 
