<TEXT>
heavy rain fell tuesday on part of the droughtravaged northern 
plains but the roadbuckling heat wave around 100 degrees gave it 
little chance of soaking in and farmers with withered pastures 
turned to hay hot lines to find cattle feed 
on the lower mississippi river shrunken by months of low rain 
in the plains and midwest barges escaped from one lowwater 
bottleneck but faced at least one more 
temperatures hit record highs monday on the last day of spring 
across the central and eastern united states and repeated that 
tuesday for the first day of summer at more than 40 cities from the 
dakotas to the east coast the national weather service said 
thermometers didnt have far to rise to hit records tuesday 
with bismarck nd cooling down overnight only to a low of 77 a 
record a few minutes after noon the city tied its record of 99 and 
later warmed to 103 degrees 
records for high temperatures started toppling well before the 
sun was even directly overhead milwaukee tied its record of 93 at 
1034 am then broke it six minutes later and continued on to 
101 other records soon began falling across michigan iowa 
illinois south dakota north dakota and indiana 
the official highest reading in the contiguous 48 states was 114 
degrees at phoenix ariz while hill city kan hit 111 and sioux 
falls sd reached 110 twentythree states reported at least one 
city in tripledigit heat 
a cool front is expected to sweep from canada into north dakota 
minnesota upper wisconsin and upper michigan wednesday dropping 
temperatures into the 80s and giving some relief from the humidity 
the weather service said 
lightning ignited dry timber and grass in northwestern south 
dakota firefighters were trying to control one fire that burned an 
estimated 5000 acres while another scorched at least 1500 acres 
state and us forest service officials said 
many utilities hit record peak loads and asked customers to cut 
back their use of electricity iowa electric offers price breaks if 
industrial customers shut off electricity during peak demand and 
those who went for the price break included kirkwood community 
college in cedar rapids and that citys public library said 
spokeswoman colleen reilly 
