evaporating what little moisture remains in the soil 
these real hot days 95 to 100 degrees are using more 
moisture than we can stand to lose said harold hunzicker 
agricultural adviser in marion county ill were still hanging 
in there but that is not to say we couldnt have a disaster 
the effect of continuing heat and no rain shows in montana 
where the state agricultural statistics service reported monday 
that 71 percent of the states spring wheat crop was in poor or 
very poor condition compared with 62 percent a week earlier 
at dayton ohio a hay hot line was started tuesday for farmers 
seeking fodder from as far away as kansas to feed their cattle 
because their own pastures are dried out 
a lot of people havent felt the need yet said agriculture 
